[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions can help a programmer read the code, help a compiler compile it, or help the program detect its own defects.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] For the latter, some programs check assertions by actually evaluating the predicate as they run.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Then, if it is not in fact true – an assertion failure – the program considers itself to be broken and typically deliberately crashes or throws an assertion failure exception.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Programmers can use assertions to help specify programs and to reason about program correctness.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] For example, a precondition—an assertion placed at the beginning of a section of code—determines the set of states under which the programmer expects the code to execute.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] A postcondition—placed at the end—describes the expected state at the end of execution.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] The example above uses the notation for including assertions used by C.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] That notation cannot be used in existing mainstream programming languages.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] However, programmers can include unchecked assertions using the comment feature of their programming language.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] The braces included in the comment help distinguish this use of a comment from other uses.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Libraries may provide assertion features as well.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Several modern programming languages include checked assertions – statements that are checked at runtime or sometimes statically.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] If an assertion evaluates to false at runtime, an assertion failure results, which typically causes execution to abort.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] This draws attention to the location at which the logical inconsistency is detected and can be preferable to the behaviour that would otherwise result.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] The use of assertions helps the programmer design, develop, and reason about a program.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] In languages such as Eiffel, assertions form part of the design process; other languages, such as C and Java, use them only to check assumptions at runtime.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] In both cases, they can be checked for validity at runtime, but can usually also be suppressed.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions can function as a form of documentation: they can describe the state the code expects to find before it runs (its preconditions), and the state the code expects to result in when it is finished running (postconditions); they can also specify invariants of a class.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Eiffel integrates such assertions into the language and automatically extracts them to document the class.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] This forms an important part of the method of design by contract.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] This approach is also useful in languages that do not explicitly support it: the advantage of using assertion statements rather than assertions in comments is that the program can check the assertions every time it runs; if the assertion no longer holds, an error can be reported.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] This prevents the code from getting out of sync with the assertions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] For example, the following demonstrates design by contract in C++ (using C++26 contracts).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] An assertion may be used to verify that an assumption made by the programmer during the implementation of the program remains valid when the program is executed.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] In Java, `%` is the *remainder* operator (*modulo*), and in Java, if its first operand is negative, the result can also be negative (unlike the modulo used in mathematics).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Here, the programmer has assumed that `total` is non-negative, so that the remainder of a division by 2 will always be 0 or 1.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] The assertion makes this assumption explicit: if `countNumberOfUsers` does return a negative value, the program may have a bug.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] A major advantage of this technique is that when an error does occur, it is detected immediately and directly, rather than later through often obscure effects.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Since an assertion failure usually reports the code location, one can often pinpoint the error without further debugging.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions are also sometimes placed at points where the execution is not supposed to reach.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] For example, assertions could be placed at the `default` clause of the `switch` statement in languages such as C, C++, and Java.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Any case that the programmer does not handle intentionally will raise an error, and the program will abort rather than silently continuing in an erroneous state.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] In D such an assertion is added automatically when a `switch` statement doesn't contain a `default` clause.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] In Java, assertions have been a part of the language since version 1.4.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertion failures result in raising an `AssertionError` when the program is run with the appropriate flags, without which the assert statements are ignored.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] In C, they are added on by the standard header `<assert.h>` defining `assert(*assertion*)` as a macro that signals an error in the case of failure, usually terminating the program.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] In C++, both `<assert.h>` and `<cassert>` headers provide the `assert` macro.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] The danger of assertions is that they may cause side effects either by changing memory data or by changing thread timing.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions should be implemented carefully, so they cause no side effects on program code.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertion constructs in a language allow for easy test-driven development (TDD) without the use of a third-party library.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] In C#, there is no assertion macro or keyword, but instead classes `System.Diagnostics.Debug` and `System.Diagnostics.Trace` which provide `Assert()` methods.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] During the development cycle, the programmer will typically run the program with assertions enabled.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] When an assertion failure occurs, the programmer is immediately notified of the problem.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Many assertion implementations will also halt the program's execution: this is useful, since if the program continued to run after an assertion violation occurred, it might corrupt its state and make the cause of the problem more difficult to locate.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Using the information provided by the assertion failure (such as the location of the failure and perhaps a stack trace, or even the full program state if the environment supports core dumps or if the program is running in a debugger), the programmer can usually fix the problem.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Thus, assertions provide a very powerful tool in debugging.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] When a program is deployed to production, assertions are typically turned off to avoid any overhead or side effects they may have.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] In some cases, assertions are completely absent from deployed code, such as in C/C++ assertions via macros.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] In other cases, such as Java, assertions are present in the deployed code and can be turned on in the field for debugging.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions may also be used to promise the compiler that a given edge condition is not actually reachable, thereby permitting certain optimizations that would not otherwise be possible.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] In this case, disabling the assertions could actually reduce performance.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions that are checked at compile time are called static assertions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Static assertions are particularly useful in compile-time template metaprogramming, but can also be used in low-level languages like C by introducing illegal code if (and only if) the assertion fails.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] C11 and C++11 support static assertions directly through `static_assert`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] If the `(BOOLEAN CONDITION)` part evaluates to false, then the above code will not compile because the compiler will not allow two case labels with the same constant.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] The Boolean expression must be a compile-time constant value, for example `(sizeof(int)==4)` would be a valid expression in that context.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] This construct does not work at file scope (i.e., not inside a function), and so it must be wrapped inside a function.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] If the `(BOOLEAN CONDITION)` part evaluates to false, then the above code will not compile because arrays may not have a negative length.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] If, in fact, the compiler allows a negative length, then the initialization byte (the `'!'` part) should cause even such over-lenient compilers to complain.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] The Boolean expression must be a compile-time constant value, for example `(sizeof(int) == 4)` would be a valid expression in that context.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Both of these methods require a method of constructing unique names.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Modern compilers support a `__COUNTER__` preprocessor define that facilitates the construction of unique names, by returning monotonically increasing numbers for each compilation unit.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] D provides static assertions through the use of `static assert`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Most languages allow assertions to be enabled or disabled globally, and sometimes independently.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions are often enabled during development and disabled during final testing and on release to the customer.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Not checking assertions avoids the cost of evaluating the assertions while (assuming the assertions are free of side effects) still producing the same result under normal conditions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Under abnormal conditions, disabling assertion checking can mean that a program that would have aborted will continue to run.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Some languages, including C, YASS, and C++, can completely remove assertions at compile time using the preprocessor.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Similarly, launching the Python interpreter with "-O" (for "optimize") as an argument will cause the Python code generator to not emit any bytecode for asserts.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Java requires an option to be passed to the run-time engine in order to *enable* assertions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Absent the option, assertions are bypassed, but they always remain in the code unless optimised away by a JIT compiler at run-time or excluded at compile time via the programmer manually placing each assertion behind an `if (false)` clause.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Programmers can build checks into their code that are always active by bypassing or manipulating the language's normal assertion-checking mechanisms.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions are distinct from routine error-handling.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions document logically impossible situations and discover programming errors: if the impossible occurs, then something fundamental is clearly wrong with the program.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] This is distinct from error handling: most error conditions are possible, although some may be extremely unlikely to occur in practice.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Using assertions as a general-purpose error handling mechanism is unwise: assertions do not allow for recovery from errors; an assertion failure will normally halt the program's execution abruptly; and assertions are often disabled in production code.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions also do not display a user-friendly error message.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Here, the programmer is aware that `malloc` will return a `NULL` pointer if memory is not allocated.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] This is possible: the operating system does not guarantee that every call to `malloc` will succeed.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] If an out-of-memory error occurs, the program will immediately abort.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Without the assertion, the program would continue running until `ptr` was dereferenced, and possibly longer, depending on the specific hardware being used.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] So long as assertions are not disabled, an immediate exit is assured.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] But if a graceful failure is desired, the program has to handle the failure.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] For example, a server may have multiple clients, or may hold resources that will not be released cleanly, or it may have uncommitted changes to write to a datastore.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] In such cases, it is better to fail a single transaction than to abort abruptly.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Another error is to rely on the side effects of expressions used as arguments of an assertion.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] One should always keep in mind that assertions might not be executed at all, since their sole purpose is to verify that a condition which should always be true does, in fact, hold true.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Consequently, if the program is considered to be error-free and released, assertions may be disabled and will no longer be evaluated.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] This might look like a smart way to assign the return value of `malloc` to `ptr` and check if it is `NULL` in one step, but the `malloc` call and the assignment to `ptr` is a side effect of evaluating the expression that forms the `assert` condition.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] When the `NDEBUG` parameter is passed to the compiler, as when the program is considered to be error-free and released, the `assert()` statement is removed, so `malloc()` isn't called, rendering `ptr` uninitialised.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] This could potentially result in a segmentation fault or similar null pointer error much further down the line in program execution, causing bugs that may be sporadic and/or difficult to track down.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Programmers sometimes use a similar VERIFY(X) define to alleviate this problem.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Modern compilers may issue a warning when encountering the above code.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] Furthermore, we may, at such a point, indicate the validity of these limitations.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] The assertional method for proving the correctness of programs was advocated by Alan Turing.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] In a talk "Checking a Large Routine" at Cambridge, June 24, 1949, Turing suggested: "How can one check a large routine in the sense of making sure that it's right?
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/assertion-software-development] In order that the man who checks may not have too difficult a task, the programmer should make a number of definite *assertions* which can be checked individually, and from which the correctness of the whole program easily follows".
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p01] Although one of the design goals was to prefer changes to the libraries over changes to the core language, C++11 does make several additions to the core language.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p01] Areas of the core language that were significantly improved include multithreading support, generic programming support, uniform initialization, and performance.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p01] Significant changes were also made to the C++ Standard Library, incorporating most of the C++ Technical Report 1 (TR1) libraries, except the library of mathematical special functions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p01] C++11 was published as *ISO/IEC 14882:2011* in September 2011 and is available for a fee.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p01] The working draft most similar to the published C++11 standard is N3337, dated 16 January 2012; it has only editorial corrections from the C++11 standard.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p01] C++11 was fully supported by Clang 3.3 and later, and by GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) 4.8.1 and later.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p01] Attention to beginners is considered important, because most computer programmers will always be such, and because many beginners never widen their knowledge, limiting themselves to work in aspects of the language in which they specialize.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] One function of the C++ committee is the development of the language core.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] These language features primarily exist to provide some kind of runtime performance benefit, either of memory or of computing speed.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] C++11 adds a new non-const reference type called an rvalue reference, identified by `T&&`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This refers to temporaries that are permitted to be modified after they are initialized, for the purpose of allowing "move semantics".
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] A chronic performance problem with C++03 is the costly and unneeded deep copies that can happen implicitly when objects are passed by value.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] To illustrate the issue, consider that an `std::vector<T>` is, internally, a wrapper around a C-style array with a defined size.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] If an `std::vector<T>` temporary is created or returned from a function, it can be stored only by creating a new `std::vector<T>` and copying all the rvalue's data into it.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Then the temporary and all its memory is destroyed.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] In C++11, a move constructor of `std::vector<T>` that takes an rvalue reference to an `std::vector<T>` can copy the pointer to the internal C-style array out of the rvalue into the new `std::vector<T>`, then set the pointer inside the rvalue to null.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Since the temporary will never again be used, no code will try to access the null pointer, and because the pointer is null, its memory is not deleted when it goes out of scope.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Hence, the operation not only forgoes the expense of a deep copy, but is safe and invisible.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Rvalue references can provide performance benefits to existing code without needing to make any changes outside the standard library.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The type of the returned value of a function returning an `std::vector<T>` temporary does not need to be changed explicitly to `std::vector<T>&&` to invoke the move constructor, as temporaries are considered rvalues automatically.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] For safety reasons, some restrictions are imposed.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] A named variable will never be considered to be an rvalue even if it is declared as such.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] To get an rvalue, the function template `std::move()` should be used.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Rvalue references can also be modified only under certain circumstances, being intended to be used primarily with move constructors.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Due to the nature of the wording of rvalue references, and to some modification to the wording for lvalue references (regular references), rvalue references allow developers to provide perfect function forwarding.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] When combined with variadic templates, this ability allows for function templates that can perfectly forward arguments to another function that takes those particular arguments.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This is most useful for forwarding constructor parameters, to create factory functions that will automatically call the correct constructor for those particular arguments.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This is seen in the emplace_back set of the C++ standard library methods.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] C++ has always had the concept of constant expressions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] These are expressions such as `3 + 4` that will always yield the same results, at compile time and at runtime.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Constant expressions are optimization opportunities for compilers, and compilers frequently execute them at compile time and hardcode the results in the program.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Also, in several places, the C++ specification requires using constant expressions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Defining an array requires a constant expression, and enumerator values must be constant expressions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] However, a constant expression has never been allowed to contain a function call or object constructor.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This was not valid in C++03, because `getFive() + 7` is not a constant expression.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] A C++03 compiler has no way of knowing if `getFive()` actually is constant at runtime.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] In theory, this function could affect a global variable, call other non-runtime constant functions, etc.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] C++11 introduced the keyword `constexpr`, which allows the user to guarantee that a function or object constructor is a compile-time constant.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This allows the compiler to understand, and verify, that `getFive()` is a compile-time constant.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Using `constexpr` on a function imposes some limits on what that function can do.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] First, the function must have a non-void return type.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Second, the function body cannot declare variables or define new types.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Third, the body may contain only declarations, null statements and a single return statement.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] There must exist argument values such that, after argument substitution, the expression in the return statement produces a constant expression.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Before C++11, the values of variables could be used in constant expressions only if the variables are declared const, have an initializer which is a constant expression, and are of integral or enumeration type.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Such data variables are implicitly const, and must have an initializer which must be a constant expression.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] To construct constant expression data values from user-defined types, constructors can also be declared with `constexpr`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] A `constexpr` constructor's function body can contain only declarations and null statements, and cannot declare variables or define types, as with a `constexpr` function.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] There must exist argument values such that, after argument substitution, it initializes the class's members with constant expressions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The destructors for such types must be trivial.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The copy constructor for a type with any `constexpr` constructors should usually also be defined as a `constexpr` constructor, to allow objects of the type to be returned by value from a constexpr function.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Any member function of a class, such as copy constructors, operator overloads, etc., can be declared as `constexpr`, so long as they meet the requirements for constexpr functions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This allows the compiler to copy objects at compile time, perform operations on them, etc.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] If a constexpr function or constructor is called with arguments which aren't constant expressions, the call behaves as if the function were not constexpr, and the resulting value is not a constant expression.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Likewise, if the expression in the return statement of a constexpr function does not evaluate to a constant expression for a given invocation, the result is not a constant expression.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] `constexpr` differs from `consteval`, introduced in C++20, in that the latter must always produce a compile time constant, while `constexpr` does not have this restriction.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] In C++03, a class or struct must follow a number of rules for it to be considered a plain old data (POD) type.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Types that fit this definition produce object layouts that are compatible with C, and they could also be initialized statically.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] C++11 relaxed several of the POD rules, by dividing the POD concept into two separate concepts: *trivial* and *standard-layout*.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] A type that is *trivial* can be statically initialized.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] It also means that it is valid to copy data around via `std::memcpy()`, rather than having to use a copy constructor.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The lifetime of a *trivial* type begins when its storage is defined, not when a constructor completes.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Has trivial copy and move constructors, which may use the default syntax.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Has trivial copy and move assignment operators, which may use the default syntax.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Has a trivial destructor, which must not be virtual.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Constructors are trivial only if there are no virtual member functions of the class and no virtual base classes.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Copy/move operations also require all non-static data members to be trivial.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] A type that is *standard-layout* means that it orders and packs its members in a way that is compatible with C.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] A class/struct/union is considered POD if it is trivial, standard-layout, and all of its non-static data members and base classes are PODs.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] By separating these concepts, it becomes possible to give up one without losing the other.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] A class with complex move and copy constructors may not be trivial, but it could be standard-layout and thus interoperate with C.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Similarly, a class with public and private non-static data members would not be standard-layout, but it could be trivial and thus `memcpy`-able.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] In C++03, the compiler must instantiate a template whenever a fully specified template is encountered in a translation unit.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] If the template is instantiated with the same types in many translation units, this can dramatically increase compile times.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] There is no way to prevent this in C++03, so C++11 introduced extern template declarations, analogous to extern data declarations.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] which tells the compiler *not* to instantiate the template in this translation unit.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] These features exist for the primary purpose of making the language easier to use.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] These can improve type safety, minimize code repetition, make erroneous code less likely, etc.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] C++03 inherited the initializer-list feature from C.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] A struct or array is given a list of arguments in braces, in the order of the members' definitions in the struct.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] These initializer-lists are recursive, so an array of structs or struct containing other structs can use them.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This is very useful for static lists, or initializing a struct to some value.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] C++ also provides constructors to initialize an object, but they are often not as convenient as the initializer list.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] However, C++03 allows initializer-lists only on structs and classes that conform to the Plain Old Data (POD) definition; C++11 extends initializer-lists, so they can be used for all classes including standard containers like `std::vector<T>`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] C++11 binds the concept to a template, called `std::initializer_list<T>`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This allows constructors and other functions to take initializer-lists as parameters.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This constructor is a special kind of constructor, called an initializer-list-constructor.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The template class `std::initializer_list<T>` is a first-class C++11 standard library type.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The list can be copied once constructed, which is cheap and will act as a copy-by-reference (the class is typically implemented as a pair of begin/end pointers).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] An `std::initializer_list<T>` is constant: its members cannot be changed once it is created, and nor can the data in those members be changed (which rules out moving from them, requiring copies into class members, etc.).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Although its construction is specially treated by the compiler, an `std::initializer_list<T>` is a real type, and so it can be used in other places besides class constructors.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Regular functions can take typed `std::initializer_list<T>`s as arguments.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Examples of this in the standard library include the `std::min()` and `std::max()` templates taking `std::initializer_list<T>`s of numeric type.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] C++03 has a number of problems with initializing types.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Several ways to do this exist, and some produce different results when interchanged.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The traditional constructor syntax, for example, can look like a function declaration, and steps must be taken to ensure that the compiler's most vexing parse rule will not mistake it for such.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Only aggregates and POD types can be initialized with aggregate initializers (using `T x = { /* initialization */ };`).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] C++11 provides a syntax that allows for fully uniform type initialization that works on any object.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The initialization of `v1` behaves exactly as though it were aggregate-initialization.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] That is, each data member of an object, in turn, will be copy-initialized with the corresponding value from the initializer-list.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Implicit type conversion will be used where needed.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] If no conversion exists, or only a narrowing conversion exists, the program is ill-formed.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The initialization of `v2` invokes the constructor.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Uniform initialization does not replace constructor syntax, which is still needed at times.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] If a class has an initializer list constructor (`T(initializer_list<X> v);`), then it takes priority over other forms of construction, provided that the initializer list conforms to the sequence constructor's type.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The C++11 version of `std::vector<T>` has an initializer list constructor for its template type.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] will call the initializer list constructor, not the constructor of `std::vector` that takes a single size parameter and creates the vector with that size.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] To access the latter constructor, the user will need to use the standard constructor syntax directly.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] In C++03 (and C), to use a variable, its type must be specified explicitly.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] However, with the advent of template types and template metaprogramming techniques, the type of something, particularly the well-defined return value of a function, may not be easily expressed.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Thus, storing intermediates in variables is difficult, possibly needing knowledge of the internals of a given metaprogramming library.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] C++11 allows this to be mitigated in two ways.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] First, the definition of a variable with an explicit initialization can use the `auto` keyword.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The type of `callable` is simply whatever the particular template function override of `std::bind()` returns for those particular arguments.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This type is easily determined procedurally by the compiler as part of its semantic analysis duties, but is not easy for the user to determine upon inspection.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The type of `y` is also well-defined, but it is easier for the user to determine.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] It is an `int`, which is the same type as the integer literal.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This use of the keyword `auto` in C++ re-purposes the semantics of this keyword, which was originally used in the typeless predecessor language B in a related role of denoting an untyped automatic variable definition.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Further, the keyword `decltype` can be used to determine the type of expression at compile-time.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This is more useful in conjunction with `auto`, since the type of auto variable is known only to the compiler.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] However, `decltype` can also be very useful for expressions in code that makes heavy use of operator overloading and specialized types.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] `auto` is also useful for reducing the verbosity of the code.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This difference grows as the programmer begins to nest containers, though in such cases `typedef`s may be used to decrease the amount of code.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The type denoted by `decltype` can be different from the type deduced by `auto`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This form of `for`, called the “range-based for”, will iterate over each element in the list.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] It will work for C-style arrays (provided its length is known at compile time), initializer lists, and any type that has `begin()` and `end()` functions defined for it that return iterators.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] All standard library containers that have begin/end pairs will work with the range-based for statement.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] C++11 provides the ability to create anonymous functions, called lambda functions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The return type (`-> int` in this example) can be omitted as long as all `return` expressions return the same type.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Standard C function declaration syntax was perfectly adequate for the feature set of the C language.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] As C++ evolved from C, it kept the basic syntax and extended it where needed.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] However, as C++ grew more complex, it exposed several limits, especially regarding template function declarations.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The type `Ret` is whatever the addition of types `L` and `R` will produce.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This is not valid C++ because `lhs` and `rhs` have not yet been defined; they will not be valid identifiers until after the parser has parsed the rest of the function prototype.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The use of the "`auto`" keyword in this case is just part of the syntax and does not perform automatic type deduction in C++11.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] However, starting with C++14, the trailing return type can be removed entirely and the compiler will deduce the return type automatically.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] In C++03, constructors of a class are not allowed to call other constructors in an initializer list of that class.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Constructors for base classes cannot be directly exposed to derived classes; each derived class must implement constructors even if a base class constructor would be appropriate.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Non-constant data members of classes cannot be initialized at the site of the declaration of those members.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] They can be initialized only in a constructor.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] C++11 provides solutions to all of these problems.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] C++11 allows constructors to call other peer constructors (termed delegation).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This allows constructors to utilize another constructor's behavior with a minimum of added code.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Delegation has been used in other languages e.g., Java and Objective-C.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] In this case, the same effect could have been achieved by making `number` a default parameter.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This comes with a caveat: C++03 considers an object to be constructed when its constructor finishes executing, but C++11 considers an object constructed once *any* constructor finishes execution.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Since multiple constructors will be allowed to execute, this will mean that each delegating constructor will be executing on a fully constructed object of its own type.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Derived class constructors will execute after all delegation in their base classes is complete.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] For base-class constructors, C++11 allows a class to specify that base class constructors will be inherited.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Thus, the C++11 compiler will generate code to perform the inheritance and the forwarding of the derived class to the base class.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This is an all-or-nothing feature: either all of that base class's constructors are forwarded or none of them are.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Also, an inherited constructor will be shadowed if it matches the signature of a constructor of the derived class, and restrictions exist for multiple inheritance: class constructors cannot be inherited from two classes that use constructors with the same signature.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Any constructor of the class will initialize `value` with 5, if the constructor does not override the initialization with its own.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] So the above empty constructor will initialize `value` as the class definition states, but the constructor that takes an int will initialize it to the given parameter.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] It can also use constructor or uniform initialization, instead of the assignment initialization shown above.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] In C++03, it is possible to accidentally create a new virtual function, when one intended to override a base class function.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] Suppose the `Derived::foo()` is intended to replace the base class version.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] But instead, because it has a different signature, it creates a second virtual function.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] This is a common problem, particularly when a user goes to modify the base class.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] C++11 provides syntax to solve this problem.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] The `override` special identifier means that the compiler will check the base class(es) to see if there is a virtual function with this exact signature.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p02] And if there is not, the compiler will indicate an error.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++11 also adds the ability to prevent inheriting from classes or simply preventing overriding methods in derived classes.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] This is done with the special identifier `final`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In this example, the `virtual void foo() final;` statement declares a new virtual function, but it also prevents derived classes from overriding it.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] It also has the effect of preventing derived classes from using that particular function name and parameter combination.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Neither `override` nor `final` are language keywords.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] For the purposes of this section and this section alone, every occurrence of "`0`" is meant as "a constant expression which evaluates to `0`, which is of type int".
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In reality, the constant expression can be of any integral type.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Since the dawn of C in 1972, the constant `0` has had the double role of constant integer and null pointer constant.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The ambiguity inherent in the double meaning of `0` was dealt with in C by using the preprocessor macro `NULL`, which commonly expands to either `((void*)0)` or `0`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++ forbids implicit conversion from `void*` to other pointer types, thus removing the benefit of casting `0` to `void*`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] As a consequence, only `0` is allowed as a null pointer constant.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] If `NULL` is defined as `0` (which is usually the case in C++), the statement `foo(NULL);` will call `foo(int i)`, which is almost certainly not what the programmer intended, and not what a superficial reading of the code suggests.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++11 corrects this by introducing a new keyword to serve as a distinguished null pointer constant: `nullptr`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] It is of type `nullptr_t`, which is implicitly convertible and comparable to any pointer type or pointer-to-member type.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] It is not implicitly convertible or comparable to integral types, except for `bool`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] While the original proposal specified that an rvalue of type `nullptr_t` should not be convertible to `bool`, the core language working group decided that such a conversion would be desirable, for consistency with regular pointer types.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The proposed wording changes were unanimously voted into the Working Paper in June 2008.[1] A similar proposal was also brought to the C standard working group and was accepted for inclusion in C23.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] For backwards compatibility reasons, `0` remains a valid null pointer constant.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In C++03, enumerations are not type-safe.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] They are effectively integers, even when the enumeration types are distinct.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] This allows the comparison between two enum values of different enumeration types.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The only safety that C++03 provides is that an integer or a value of one enum type does not convert implicitly to another enum type.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Further, the underlying integral type is implementation-defined; code that depends on the size of the enumeration is thus non-portable.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Lastly, enumeration values are scoped to the enclosing scope.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Thus, it is not possible for two separate enumerations in the same scope to have matching member names.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++11 allows a special classification of enumeration that has none of these issues.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Enum class values are not implicitly converted to integers.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Thus, they cannot be compared to integers either (the expression `CardSuit::SPADES == 8` gives a compile error).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The underlying type of enum classes is always known.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] With old-style enumerations the values are placed in the outer scope.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] With new-style enumerations they are placed within the scope of the enum class name.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] So in the above example, `UP` is undefined, but `Direction::UP` is defined.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In this case the enumerator names are defined in the enumeration's scope (`Direction::UP`), but for backwards compatibility they are also placed in the enclosing scope.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Forward-declaring enums is also possible in C++11.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Formerly, enum types could not be forward-declared because the size of the enumeration depends on the definition of its members.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++03's parser defines “`>>`” as the right shift operator or stream extraction operator in all cases.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] However, with nested template declarations, there is a tendency for the programmer to neglect to place a space between the two right angle brackets, thus causing a compiler syntax error.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++11 improves the specification of the parser so that multiple right angle brackets will be interpreted as closing the template argument list where it is reasonable.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++98 added the `explicit` keyword as a modifier on constructors to prevent single-argument constructors from being used as implicit type conversion operators.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] However, this does nothing for actual conversion operators.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] For example, a smart pointer class may have an `operator bool()` to allow it to act more like a primitive pointer: if it includes this conversion, it can be tested with `if (p)` (which would be true if the pointer was non-null and false otherwise).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] However, this allows other, unintended conversions as well.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Because C++ `bool` is defined as an arithmetic type, it can be implicitly converted to integral or even floating-point types, which allows for mathematical operations that are not intended by the user.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In C++11, the `explicit` keyword can now be applied to conversion operators.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] As with constructors, it prevents using those conversion functions in implicit conversions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] However, language contexts that specifically need a Boolean value (the conditions of if-statements and loops, and operands to the logical operators) count as explicit conversions and can thus use a bool conversion operator.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] For example, this feature solves cleanly the safe bool issue.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In C++03, it is possible to define a typedef only as a synonym for another type, including a synonym for a template specialization with all actual template arguments specified.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] It is not possible to create a typedef template.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In C++03, there are restrictions on what types of objects can be members of a `union`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] For example, unions cannot contain any objects that define a non-trivial constructor or destructor.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] If a `union` member has a non trivial special member function, the compiler will not generate the equivalent member function for the `union` and it must be manually defined.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The changes will not break any existing code since they only relax current rules.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] These features allow the language to do things that were formerly impossible, exceedingly verbose, or needed non-portable libraries.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In C++11, templates can take variable numbers of template parameters.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] This also allows the definition of type-safe variadic functions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++03 offers two kinds of string literals.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The first kind, contained within double quotes, produces a null-terminated array of type `const char`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The second kind, defined as `L""`, produces a null-terminated array of type `const wchar_t`, where `wchar_t` is a wide-character of undefined size and semantics.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Neither literal type offers support for string literals with UTF-8, UTF-16, or any other kind of Unicode encodings.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++11 supports three Unicode encodings: UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The definition of the type `char` has been modified to explicitly express that it is at least the size needed to store an eight-bit coding of UTF-8, and large enough to contain any member of the compiler's basic execution character set.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] It was formerly defined as only the latter in the C++ standard itself, then relying on the C standard to guarantee at least 8 bits.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Furthermore, C++11 adds two new character types: `char16_t` and `char32_t`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] These are designed to store UTF-16 and UTF-32 respectively.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The type of the first string is the usual `const char[]`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The type of the second string is `const char16_t[]` (note lower case 'u' prefix).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The type of the third string is `const char32_t[]` (upper case 'U' prefix).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] When building Unicode string literals, it is often useful to insert Unicode code points directly into the string.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The number after the `\u` is a hexadecimal number; it does not need the usual `0x` prefix.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The identifier `\u` represents a 16-bit Unicode code point; to enter a 32-bit code point, use `\U` and a 32-bit hexadecimal number.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Only valid Unicode code points can be entered.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] For example, code points on the range U+D800–U+DFFF are forbidden, as they are reserved for surrogate pairs in UTF-16 encodings.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] It is also sometimes useful to avoid escaping strings manually, particularly for using literals of XML files, scripting languages, or regular expressions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In the first case, everything between the `"(` and the `)"` is part of the string.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The `"` and `\` characters do not need to be escaped.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In the second case, the `"delimiter(` starts the string, and it ends only when `)delimiter"` is reached.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The string `delimiter` can be any string up to 16 characters in length, including the empty string.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] This string cannot contain spaces, control characters, `(`, `)`, or the `\` character.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Using this delimiter string, the user can have the sequence `)"` within raw string literals.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The characters `12.5` are a literal that is resolved by the compiler as a type `double` with the value of 12.5.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] However, the addition of the suffix `f`, as in `12.5f`, creates a value of type `float` that contains the value 12.5.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The suffix modifiers for literals are fixed by the C++ specification, and C++03 code cannot create new literal modifiers.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] By contrast, C++11 enables the user to define new kinds of literal modifiers that will construct objects based on the string of characters that the literal modifies.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Transformation of literals is redefined into two distinct phases: raw and cooked.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] A raw literal is a sequence of characters of some specific type, while the cooked literal is of a separate type.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] As a cooked literal, it is the integer 1234.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The C++ literal `0xA` in raw form is `'0'`, `'x'`, `'A'`, while in cooked form it is the integer 10.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Literals can be extended in both raw and cooked forms, with the exception of string literals, which can be processed only in cooked form.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] This exception is due to the fact that strings have prefixes that affect the specific meaning and type of the characters in question.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] All user-defined literals are suffixes; defining prefix literals is not possible.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] All suffixes starting with any character except underscore (`_`) are reserved by the standard.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Thus, all user-defined literals should have suffixes starting with an underscore (`_`).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] User-defined literals processing the raw form of the literal are defined via a literal operator, which is written as `operator""`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The assignment statement `MyOutput x = 1234_suf;` executes the code defined by the user-defined literal function.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] This function is passed `"1234"` as a C-style string, so it has a null terminator.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] This instantiates the literal processing function as `operator""_suf<'1', '2', '3', '4'>()`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In this form, there is no null character terminating the string.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The main purpose for doing this is to use C++11's `constexpr` keyword to ensure that the compiler will transform the literal entirely at compile time, assuming `MyOutput` is a constexpr-constructible and copyable type, and the literal processing function is a `constexpr` function.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] For numeric literals, the type of the cooked literal is either `unsigned long long` for integral literals or `long double` for floating point literals.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Character literals are defined similarly.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++11 standardizes support for multithreaded programming.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] There are two parts involved: a memory model which allows multiple threads to co-exist in a program and library support for interaction between threads.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The memory model defines when multiple threads may access the same memory location, and specifies when updates by one thread become visible to other threads.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In a multi-threaded environment, it is common for every thread to have some unique variables.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] This already happens for the local variables of a function, but it does not happen for global and static variables.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] A new *thread-local* storage duration (in addition to the existing *static*, *dynamic* and *automatic*) is indicated by the storage specifier `thread_local`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Any object which could have static storage duration (i.e., lifetime spanning the entire execution of the program) may be given thread-local duration instead.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The intent is that like any other static-duration variable, a thread-local object can be initialized using a constructor and destroyed using a destructor.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In C++03, the compiler provides, for classes that do not provide them for themselves, a default constructor, a copy constructor, a copy assignment operator (`operator=`), and a destructor.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The programmer can override these defaults by defining custom versions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++ also defines several global operators (such as `operator new`) that work on all classes, which the programmer can override.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] However, there is very little control over creating these defaults.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Making a class inherently non-copyable, for example, may be done by declaring a private copy constructor and copy assignment operator and not defining them.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Attempting to use these functions is a violation of the One Definition Rule (ODR).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] While a diagnostic message is not required, violations may result in a linker error.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In the case of the default constructor, the compiler will not generate a default constructor if a class is defined with *any* constructors.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] This is useful in many cases, but it is also useful to be able to have both specialized constructors and the compiler-generated default.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++11 allows the explicit defaulting and deleting of these special member functions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] This is useful for preventing implicit type conversions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The `= delete` specifier can be used to prohibit calling a function with particular parameter types.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] An attempt to call `noInt()` with an `int` parameter will be rejected by the compiler, instead of performing a silent conversion to `double`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Calling `noInt()` with a `float` still works.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] calling `onlyDouble(1.0)` will work, while `onlyDouble(1.0f)` will generate a compiler error.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Class member functions and constructors can also be deleted.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In C++03, the largest integer type is `long int`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] It is guaranteed to have at least as many usable bits as `int`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] This resulted in `long int` having size of 64 bits on some popular implementations and 32 bits on others.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++11 adds a new integer type `long long int` to address this issue.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] It is guaranteed to be at least as large as a `long int`, and have no fewer than 64 bits.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The type was originally introduced by C99 to the standard C, and most C++ compilers supported it as an extension already.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++03 provides two methods to test assertions: the macro `assert` and the preprocessor directive `#error`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] However, neither is appropriate for use in templates: the macro tests the assertion at execution-time, while the preprocessor directive tests the assertion during preprocessing, which happens before instantiation of templates.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Neither is appropriate for testing properties that are dependent on template parameters.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The new utility introduces a new way to test assertions at compile-time, using the new keyword `static_assert`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] When the constant expression is `false` the compiler produces an error message.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The first example is similar to the preprocessor directive `#error`, although the preprocessor does only support integral types.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In contrast, in the second example the assertion is checked at every instantiation of the template class `Check`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Static assertions are useful outside of templates also.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] For instance, a given implementation of an algorithm might depend on the size of a `long long` being larger than an `int`, something the standard does not guarantee.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Such an assumption is valid on most systems and compilers, but not all.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In C++03, the `sizeof` operator can be used on types and objects.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++03 disallows this, so it is a compile error.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] It is also allowed for the `alignof` operator introduced in C++11.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++11 allows variable alignment to be queried and controlled with `alignof` and `alignas`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The `alignof` operator takes the type and returns the power of 2 byte boundary on which the type instances must be allocated (as a `std::size_t`).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] When given a reference type `alignof` returns the referenced type's alignment; for arrays it returns the element type's alignment.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The `alignas` specifier controls the memory alignment for a variable.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] The specifier takes a constant or a type; when supplied a type `alignas(T)` is shorthand for `alignas(alignof(T))`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Prior C++ standards provided for programmer-driven garbage collection, but gave no definition of object reachability for the purpose of automatic garbage collection.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++11 defines conditions under which pointer values are "safely derived" from other values.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] An implementation may specify that it operates under *strict pointer safety*, in which case pointers that are not derived according to these rules can become invalid.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++11 provides a standardized syntax for compiler/tool extensions to the language.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Such extensions were traditionally specified using `#pragma` directive or vendor-specific keywords (like `__attribute__` for GNU and `__declspec` for Microsoft).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] With the new syntax, added information can be specified in a form of an attribute enclosed in double square brackets.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] In the example above, attribute `[[attr1]]` applies to the type of variable `i`, `[[attr2]]` and `[[attr3]]` apply to the variable itself, `[[attr4]]` applies to the `if` statement and `[[vendor::attr5]]` applies to the return statement.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] It is recommended that attributes have no language semantic meaning and do not change the sense of a program when ignored.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] Attributes can be useful for providing information that, for example, helps the compiler to issue better diagnostics or optimize the generated code.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p03] C++11 provides two standard attributes itself: `[[noreturn]]` to specify that a function does not return, and `[[carries_dependency]]` to help optimizing multi-threaded code by indicating that function arguments or return value carry a dependency.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] A number of new features were introduced in the C++11 standard library.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Many of these could have been implemented under the old standard, but some rely (to a greater or lesser extent) on new C++11 core features.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] A large part of the new libraries was defined in the document *C++ Standards Committee's Library Technical Report* (called TR1), which was published in 2005.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Various full and partial implementations of TR1 are currently available using the namespace `std::tr1`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] For C++11 they were moved to namespace `std`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] However, as TR1 features were brought into the C++11 standard library, they were upgraded where appropriate with C++11 language features that were not available in the initial TR1 version.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Also, they may have been enhanced with features that were possible under C++03, but were not part of the original TR1 specification.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] C++11 offers a number of new language features that the currently existing standard library components can benefit from.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] For example, most standard library containers can benefit from Rvalue reference based move constructor support, both for quickly moving heavy containers around and for moving the contents of those containers to new memory locations.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The standard library components were upgraded with new C++11 language features where appropriate.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Further, much time has passed since the prior C++ standard.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Much code using the standard library has been written.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] This has revealed parts of the standard libraries that could use some improving.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Among the many areas of improvement considered were standard library allocators.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] A new scope-based model of allocators was included in C++11 to supplement the prior model.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] While the C++03 language provides a memory model that supports threading, the primary support for actually using threading comes with the C++11 standard library.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] A thread class (`std::thread`) is provided, which takes a function object (and an optional series of arguments to pass to it) to run in the new thread.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] It is possible to cause a thread to halt until another executing thread completes, providing thread joining support via the `std::thread::join()` member function.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Access is provided, where feasible, to the underlying native thread object(s) for platform-specific operations by the `std::thread::native_handle()` member function.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] For synchronization between threads, appropriate mutexes (`std::mutex`, `std::recursive_mutex`, etc.) and condition variables (`std::condition_variable` and `std::condition_variable_any`) are added to the library.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] These are accessible via Resource Acquisition Is Initialization (RAII) locks (`std::lock_guard` and `std::unique_lock`) and locking algorithms for easy use.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] For high-performance, low-level work, communicating between threads is sometimes needed without the overhead of mutexes.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] This is done using atomic operations on memory locations.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] These can optionally specify the minimum memory visibility constraints needed for an operation.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Explicit memory barriers may also be used for this purpose.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The C++11 thread library also includes futures and promises for passing asynchronous results between threads, and `std::packaged_task` for wrapping up a function call that can generate such an asynchronous result.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The futures proposal was criticized because it lacks a way to combine futures and check for the completion of one promise inside a set of promises.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Further high-level threading facilities such as thread pools have been remanded to a future C++ technical report.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] They are not part of C++11, but their eventual implementation is expected to be built entirely on top of the thread library features.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The new `std::async` facility provides a convenient method of running tasks and tying them to a `std::future`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The user can choose whether the task is to be run asynchronously on a separate thread or synchronously on a thread that waits for the value.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] By default, the implementation can choose, which provides an easy way to take advantage of hardware concurrency without oversubscription, and provides some of the advantages of a thread pool for simple usages.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Tuples are collections composed of heterogeneous objects of pre-arranged dimensions.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] A tuple can be considered a generalization of a struct's member variables.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The C++11 version of the TR1 tuple type benefited from C++11 features like variadic templates.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] To implement reasonably, the TR1 version required an implementation-defined maximum number of contained types, and substantial macro trickery.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] By contrast, the implementation of the C++11 version requires no explicit implementation-defined maximum number of types.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Though compilers will have an internal maximum recursion depth for template instantiation (which is normal), the C++11 version of tuples will not expose this value to the user.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] It's possible to create the tuple `proof` without defining its contents, but only if the tuple elements' types possess default constructors.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Just like `std::make_pair` for `std::pair`, there exists `std::make_tuple` to automatically create `std::tuple`s using type deduction and `auto` helps to declare such a tuple.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] `std::tie` creates tuples of lvalue references to help unpack tuples.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Including hash tables (unordered associative containers) in the C++ standard library is one of the most recurring requests.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] It was not adopted in C++03 due to time constraints only.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Although hash tables are less efficient than a balanced tree in the worst case (in the presence of many collisions), they perform better in many real applications.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Collisions are managed only via *linear chaining* because the committee didn't consider it to be opportune to standardize solutions of *open addressing* that introduce quite a lot of intrinsic problems (above all when erasure of elements is admitted).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] To avoid name clashes with non-standard libraries that developed their own hash table implementations, the prefix “unordered” was used instead of “hash”.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The new library has four types of hash tables, differentiated by whether or not they accept elements with the same key (unique keys or equivalent keys), and whether they map each key to an associated value.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] They correspond to the four existing binary search tree based associative containers, with an unordered_ prefix.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The new classes fulfill all the requirements of a container class, and have all the methods needed to access elements: `insert`, `erase`, `begin`, `end`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] This new feature didn't need any C++ language core extensions (though implementations will take advantage of various C++11 language features), only a small extension of the header `<functional>` and the introduction of headers `<unordered_set>` and `<unordered_map>`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] No other changes to any existing standard classes were needed, and it doesn't depend on any other extensions of the standard library.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] In addition to the hash tables two more containers were added to the standard library.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The `std::array` is a fixed-size container that is more efficient than `std::vector` but safer and easier to use than a C-style array.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The `std::forward_list` is a singly-linked list that provides more space efficient storage than the double linked `std::list` when bidirectional iteration is not needed.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The function `std::regex_search` is used for searching, while for ‘search and replace’ the function `std::regex_replace` is used which returns a new string.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The library `<regex>` requires neither alteration of any existing header (though it will use them where appropriate) nor an extension of the core language.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] In POSIX C, regular expressions are also available via the <regex.h>.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] C++11 provides `std::unique_ptr`, and improvements to `std::shared_ptr` and `std::weak_ptr` from TR1.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The C standard library provides the ability to generate pseudorandom numbers via the function `rand`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] However, the algorithm is delegated entirely to the library vendor.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] C++ inherited this functionality with no changes, but C++11 provides a new method for generating pseudorandom numbers.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] C++11's random number functionality is split into two parts: a generator engine that contains the random number generator's state and produces the pseudorandom numbers; and a distribution, which determines the range and mathematical distribution of the outcome.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] These two are combined to form a random number generator object.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] A wrapper reference is obtained from an instance of the class template `reference_wrapper`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Wrapper references are similar to normal references (‘`&`’) of the C++ language.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] To obtain a wrapper reference from any object the function template `ref` is used (for a constant reference `cref` is used).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] This new utility was added to the existing `<functional>` header and didn't need further extensions of the C++ language.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The template class `function` was defined inside the header `<functional>`, without needing any change to the C++ language.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Metaprogramming consists of creating a program that creates or modifies another program (or itself).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] This can happen during compilation or during execution.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The C++ Standards Committee has decided to introduce a library for metaprogramming during compiling via templates.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Many algorithms can operate on different types of data; C++'s templates support generic programming and make code more compact and useful.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Nevertheless, it is common for algorithms to need information on the data types being used.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] This information can be extracted during instantiation of a template class using *type traits*.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] In the next example there is the template function 'elaborate' which, depending on the given data types, will instantiate one of the two proposed algorithms (`Algorithm::perform`).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Via *type traits*, defined in header `<type_traits>`, it's also possible to create type transformation operations (`static_cast` and `const_cast` are insufficient inside a template).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] This type of programming produces elegant and concise code; however, the weak point of these techniques is the debugging: it's uncomfortable during compilation and very difficult during program execution.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Determining the return type of a template function object at compile-time is not intuitive, particularly if the return value depends on the parameters of the function.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Instantiating the class template `Calculus<Clear>`, the function object of `calculus` will have always the same return type as the function object of `Clear`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Attempting to instantiate `Calculus<Confused>` will cause the return type of `Calculus` to not be the same as that of class `Confused`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The compiler may generate warnings about the conversion from `int` to `double` and vice versa.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] TR1 introduces, and C++11 adopts, the template class `std::result_of` that allows one to determine and use the return type of a function object for every declaration.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] In this way in instances of function object of `CalculusVer2<Confused>` there are no conversions, warnings, or errors.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The only change from the TR1 version of `std::result_of` is that the TR1 version allowed an implementation to fail to be able to determine the result type of a function call.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Due to changes to C++ for supporting `decltype`, the C++11 version of `std::result_of` no longer needs these special cases; implementations are required to compute a type in all cases.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The term sequence point was removed, being replaced by specifying that either one operation is sequenced before another, or that two operations are unsequenced.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The use of the keyword `export`, along with exported templates, were removed.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] The `export` keyword remained reserved, and was later reintroduced in C++20 with the addition of modules.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Dynamic exception specifications are deprecated.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Compile-time specification of non-exception-throwing functions is available with the `noexcept` keyword, which is useful for optimization.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] `std::auto_ptr` is deprecated, having been superseded by `std::unique_ptr`.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c-11-p04] Function object base classes (`std::unary_function`, `std::binary_function`), adapters to pointers to functions and adapters to pointers to members, and binder classes are all deprecated.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] C++ was designed with systems programming and embedded, resource-constrained software and large systems in mind, with performance, efficiency, and flexibility of use as its design highlights.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), with the latest standard version ratified and published by ISO in October 2024 as *ISO/IEC 14882:2024* (informally known as C++23).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] The C++ programming language was initially standardized in 1998 as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which was then amended by the C++03, C++11, C++14, C++17, and C++20 standards.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] The next C++23 standard superseded these with new features and an enlarged standard library.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] Before the initial standardization in 1998, C++ was developed by Stroustrup at Bell Labs since 1979 as an extension of the C language; he wanted an efficient and flexible language similar to C that also provided high-level features for program organization.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] Since 2012, C++ has been on a three-year release schedule with C++29 as the next planned standard.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] In 1979, Bjarne Stroustrup, a Danish computer scientist, began work on "C with Classes", the predecessor to C++.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] The motivation for creating a new language originated from Stroustrup's experience in programming for his PhD thesis.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup found that Simula had features that were very helpful for large software development, but the language was too slow for practical use, while BCPL was fast but too low-level to be suitable for large software development.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] When Stroustrup started working in AT&T Bell Labs, he had the problem of analyzing the UNIX kernel with respect to distributed computing.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] Remembering his PhD experience, Stroustrup set out to enhance the C language with Simula-like features.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] C was chosen because it was general-purpose, fast, portable, and widely used.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] In addition to C and Simula's influences, other languages influenced this new language, including ALGOL 68, Ada, CLU, and ML.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] Initially, Stroustrup's "C with Classes" added features to the C compiler, Cpre, including classes, derived classes, strong typing, inlining, and default arguments.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] In 1982, Stroustrup began designing a cleaned-up and extended successor to C with Classes, using traditional compiler technology.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] The language was briefly called C84 before the name C++ was adopted; the name was suggested by Rick Mascitti and refers to C's `++` increment operator.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] The resulting language included virtual functions, function and operator overloading, references, `const`, improved type checking, user-controlled free-store memory allocation (`new`/`delete`), and BCPL-style single-line `//` comments.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup also designed and implemented Cfront, the C++ compiler front end, between spring 1982 and summer 1983.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] In 1984, Stroustrup implemented the first stream input/output library.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] The idea of providing an output operator rather than a named output function was suggested by Doug McIlroy (who had previously suggested Unix pipes).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] In 1985, the first edition of *The C++ Programming Language* was released, which became the definitive reference for the language, as there was not yet an official standard.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] The first commercial implementation of C++ was released in October of the same year.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] In 1989, C++ 2.0 was released, followed by the updated second edition of *The C++ Programming Language* in 1991.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] New features in 2.0 included multiple inheritance, abstract classes, static member functions, const member functions, and protected members.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] In 1990, *The Annotated C++ Reference Manual* was published.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] This work became the basis for the future standard.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] Later feature additions included templates, exceptions, namespaces, new casts, and a Boolean type.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, C++98 was released, standardizing the language, and a minor update (C++03) was released in 2003.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] After C++98, C++ evolved relatively slowly until, in 2011, the C++11 standard was released, adding numerous new features, enlarging the standard library further, and providing more facilities to C++ programmers.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] After a minor C++14 update released in December 2014, various new additions were introduced in C++17.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] After becoming finalized in February 2020, a draft of the C++20 standard was approved on 4 September 2020, and officially published on 15 December 2020.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] On January 3, 2018, Stroustrup was announced as the 2018 winner of the Charles Stark Draper Prize for Engineering, "for conceptualizing and developing the C++ programming language".
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] In December 2022, C++ ranked third on the TIOBE index, surpassing Java for the first time in the history of the index.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] As of November 2024, the language ranks second after Python, with Java being in third.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] In March 2025, Stroustrup issued a call for the language community to defend it.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] Since the language allows manual memory management, bugs that represent security risks such as buffer overflow may be introduced in programs when inadvertently misused by the programmer.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] According to Stroustrup, "the name signifies the evolutionary nature of the changes from C." This name is credited to Rick Mascitti (mid-1983) and was first used in December 1983.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] When Mascitti was questioned informally in 1992 about the naming, he indicated that it was given in a tongue-in-cheek spirit.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/c] The name comes from C's `++` operator (which increments the value of a variable) and a common naming convention of using "+" to indicate an enhanced computer program.
