[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] TDD has been adopted outside of software development, in both product and service teams, as **test-driven work**.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] For testing to be successful, it needs to be practiced at the micro and macro levels.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] Every method in a class, every input data value, log message, and error code, amongst other data points, need to be tested.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] Similar to TDD, non-software teams develop quality control (QC) checks (usually manual tests rather than automated tests) for each aspect of the work prior to commencing.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] These QC checks are then used to inform the design and validate the associated outcomes.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] There are various aspects to using test-driven development, for example the principles of "keep it simple, stupid" (KISS) and "You aren't gonna need it" (YAGNI).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] By focusing on writing only the code necessary to pass tests, designs can often be cleaner and clearer than is achieved by other methods.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] In *Test-Driven Development by Example*, Kent Beck also suggests the principle "Fake it till you make it".
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] To achieve some advanced design concept such as a design pattern, tests are written that generate that design.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] The code may remain simpler than the target pattern, but still pass all required tests.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] This can be unsettling at first but it allows the developer to focus only on what is important.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] Writing the tests first: The tests should be written before the functionality that is to be tested.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] This has been claimed to have many benefits.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] It helps ensure that the application is written for testability, as the developers must consider how to test the application from the outset rather than adding it later.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] It also ensures that tests for every feature gets written.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] Additionally, writing the tests first leads to a deeper and earlier understanding of the product requirements, ensures the effectiveness of the test code, and maintains a continual focus on software quality.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] When writing feature-first code, there is a tendency by developers and organizations to push the developer on to the next feature, even neglecting testing entirely.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] The first TDD test might not even compile at first, because the classes and methods it requires may not yet exist.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] Nevertheless, that first test functions as the beginning of an executable specification.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] Each test case fails initially: This ensures that the test really works and can catch an error.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] Once this is shown, the underlying functionality can be implemented.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] This has led to the "test-driven development mantra", which is "red/green/refactor", where red means *fail* and green means *pass*.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] Test-driven development constantly repeats the steps of adding test cases that fail, passing them, and refactoring.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] Receiving the expected test results at each stage reinforces the developer's mental model of the code, boosts confidence and increases productivity.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] In test-driven development, writing tests before implementation raises questions about testing private methods versus testing only through public interfaces.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] This choice affects the design of both test code and production code.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] Test-driven development relies primarily on unit tests for its rapid red-green-refactor cycle.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] These tests execute quickly by avoiding process boundaries, network connections, or external dependencies.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] While TDD practitioners also write integration tests to verify component interactions, these slower tests are kept separate from the more frequent unit test runs.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] Testing multiple integrated modules together also makes it more difficult to identify the source of failures.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] When code under development relies on external dependencies, TDD encourages the use of test doubles to maintain fast, isolated unit tests.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] The typical approach involves using interfaces to separate external dependencies and implementing test doubles for testing purposes.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] Since test doubles don't prove the connection to real external components, TDD practitioners supplement unit tests with integration testing at appropriate levels.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] To keep execution faster and more reliable, testing is maximized at the unit level while minimizing slower tests at higher levels.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] For TDD, a unit is most commonly defined as a class, or a group of related functions often called a module.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] Advanced practices of test-driven development can lead to acceptance test–driven development (ATDD) and specification by example where the criteria specified by the customer are automated into acceptance tests, which then drive the traditional unit test-driven development (UTDD) process.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] This process ensures the customer has an automated mechanism to decide whether the software meets their requirements.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] With ATDD, the development team now has a specific target to satisfy – the acceptance tests – which keeps them continuously focused on what the customer really wants from each user story.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/test-driven-development] Effective layout of a test case ensures all required actions are completed, improves the readability of the test case, and smooths the flow of execution.
