[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing describes tests that are run at the unit-level to contrast testing at the integration or system level.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing, as a principle for testing separately smaller parts of large software systems, dates back to the early days of software engineering.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] In June 1956 at US Navy's Symposium on Advanced Programming Methods for Digital Computers, H.D.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] It featured a specification-based approach where the coding phase was followed by "parameter testing" to validate component subprograms against their specification, followed then by an "assembly testing" for parts put together.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] In 1964, a similar approach is described for the software of the Mercury project, where individual units developed by different programmers underwent "unit tests" before being integrated together.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] In 1969, testing methodologies appear more structured, with unit tests, component tests and integration tests collectively validating individual parts written separately and their progressive assembly into larger blocks.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Some public standards adopted in the late 1960s, such as MIL-STD-483 and MIL-STD-490, contributed further to a wide acceptance of unit testing in large projects.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing was in those times interactive or automated, using either coded tests or capture and replay testing tools.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] In 1989, Kent Beck described a testing framework for Smalltalk (later called SUnit) in "Simple Smalltalk Testing: With Patterns".
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] In 1997, Kent Beck and Erich Gamma developed and released JUnit, a unit test framework that became popular with Java developers.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Google embraced automated testing around 2005–2006.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] A unit is defined as a single behaviour exhibited by the system under test (SUT), usually corresponding to a requirement.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] While a unit may correspond to a single function or module (in procedural programming) or a single method or class (in object-oriented programming), functions/methods and modules/classes do not necessarily correspond to units.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] From the system requirements perspective only the perimeter of the system is relevant, thus only entry points to externally visible system behaviours define units.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Unit tests can be performed manually or via automated test execution.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Automated tests include benefits such as: running tests often, running tests without staffing cost, and consistent and repeatable testing.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Testing is often performed by the programmer who writes and modifies the code under test.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing may be viewed as part of the process of writing code.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] During development, a programmer may code criteria, or results that are known to be good, into the test to verify the unit's correctness.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] During test execution, frameworks log tests that fail any criterion and report them in a summary.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] For this, the most commonly used approach is test - function - expected value.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Test cases underlie testing that is methodical rather than haphazard.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] A battery of test cases can be built to produce the desired coverage of the software being tested.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Formally defined test cases allow the same tests to be run repeatedly against successive versions of the software, allowing for effective and consistent regression testing.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] A test double is software used in software test automation that satisfies a dependency so that the test need not depend on production code.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] A test double provides functionality via an interface that the software under test cannot distinguish from production code.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] A parameterized test is a test that accepts a set of values that can be used to enable the test to run with multiple, different input values.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] A testing framework that supports parametrized tests supports a way to encode parameter sets and to run the test with each set.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Use of parametrized tests can reduce test code duplication.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Parameterized tests are supported by TestNG, JUnit, XUnit and NUnit, as well as in various JavaScript test frameworks.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Parameters for the unit tests may be coded manually or in some cases are automatically generated by the test framework.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] In recent years support was added for writing more powerful (unit) tests, leveraging the concept of theories, test cases that execute the same steps, but using test data generated at runtime, unlike regular parameterized tests that use the same execution steps with input sets that are pre-defined.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Test code needs access to the code it is testing, but testing should not compromise normal design goals such as information hiding, encapsulation and the separation of concerns.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] To enable access to code not exposed in the external API, unit tests can be located in the same project or module as the code being tested.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] In object oriented design this still may not provide access to private data and methods.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Therefore, extra work may be necessary for unit tests.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] In Java and other languages, a developer can use reflection to access private fields and methods.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Alternatively, an inner class can be used to hold the unit tests so they have visibility of the enclosing class's members and attributes.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] In the .NET Framework and some other programming languages, partial classes may be used to expose private methods and data for the tests to access.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] It is important that code solely for accommodating tests does not remain in the production code.
