[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Extreme programming uses the creation of unit tests for test-driven development.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] The developer writes a unit test that exposes either a software requirement or a defect.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] This test will fail because either the requirement isn't implemented yet, or because it intentionally exposes a defect in the existing code.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Then, the developer writes the simplest code to make the test, along with other tests, pass.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Most code in a system is unit tested, but not necessarily all paths through the code.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Extreme programming mandates a "test everything that can possibly break" strategy, over the traditional "test every execution path" method.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] This leads developers to develop fewer tests than classical methods, but this isn't really a problem, more a restatement of fact, as classical methods have rarely ever been followed methodically enough for all execution paths to have been thoroughly tested.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Extreme programming simply recognizes that testing is rarely exhaustive (because it is often too expensive and time-consuming to be economically viable) and provides guidance on how to effectively focus limited resources.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Crucially, the test code is considered a first class project artifact in that it is maintained at the same quality as the implementation code, with all duplication removed.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Developers release unit testing code to the code repository in conjunction with the code it tests.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Extreme programming's thorough unit testing allows the benefits mentioned above, such as simpler and more confident code development and refactoring, simplified code integration, accurate documentation, and more modular designs.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] These unit tests are also constantly run as a form of regression test.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing is also critical to the concept of Emergent Design, which develops software design iteratively through short test-driven development cycles of writing a unit test, making it pass, and refactoring; unit tests provide the regression safety net that makes continuous refactoring safe.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] An automated testing framework provides features for automating test execution and can accelerate writing and running tests.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Frameworks have been developed for a wide variety of programming languages.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Generally, frameworks are third-party, not distributed with a compiler or integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Tests can be written without using a framework to exercise the code under test using assertions, exception handling, and other control flow mechanisms to verify behavior and report failure.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] Some note that testing without a framework is valuable since there is a barrier to entry for the adoption of a framework, and that having some tests is better than none – but once a framework is in place, adding tests can be easier.
[src:catch2-cpp-lib/unit-testing] In some frameworks advanced test features are missing and must be hand-coded.
